# Intelligence of Seeing (IoS) – Cursor Operational Rules

## 1. PROJECT TYPE

This repository contains an experimental cognitive research instrument.

It is NOT:
- a production system
- a reusable framework
- an automation tool
- a commercial software product

It IS:
a controlled experimentation environment used to study structured reasoning architectures.

Cursor must treat this codebase as scientific instrumentation.


## 2. FILE STRUCTURE (MANDATORY)

Executable scripts remain at the project root.

Project directories:

/reference  → conceptual materials
/data       → experiment inputs
/outputs    → experiment logs and results

Rules:

- Never rename these directories
- Never relocate experiment outputs
- Never assume environment-specific paths
- Always use relative paths
- Use pathlib when interacting with files


## 3. SCHEMA IMMUTABILITY

All experiment logs must conform exactly to:

schema_v2.json

Cursor must NEVER:

- rename JSON keys
- remove keys
- flatten nested structures
- expand the schema
- introduce new logging fields

Schema integrity overrides convenience.

If any output violates the schema:

1. Halt execution
2. Report the exact schema violation
3. Do NOT attempt automatic repair
4. Await explicit user instruction


## 4. SINGLE-VARIABLE DISCIPLINE

The IoS project follows strict experimental methodology.

Only ONE experimental variable may change at a time.

Cursor must NOT:

- refactor unrelated components
- introduce new abstractions
- optimize performance
- restructure modules
- modify multiple systems simultaneously

Before suggesting or applying a change, Cursor must state clearly:

Variable being modified: ______


## 5. HUMAN CONSENT GATES

The Human-in-the-Loop experiment pipeline is fixed:

G–S → Human Gate → A → Human Gate → C

Cursor must NEVER:

- automate across gates
- remove user interaction
- bypass input() prompts
- simulate human responses

Human intervention is part of the experimental protocol.


## 6. PROMPT IMMUTABILITY

Prompt text defines the experimental conditions.

Cursor must NEVER:

- rewrite prompts
- adjust wording
- add instructions
- reformat prompt text
- "improve" prompts

Even minor wording changes invalidate experimental consistency.


## 7. MODEL LOCK

Model selection is part of the experiment configuration.

Cursor must NEVER:

- change model names
- substitute models
- update model versions
- introduce fallback models

Models may only change with explicit user instruction.


## 8. SIMPLICITY PRINCIPLE

This repository implements a laboratory instrument.

Cursor must prefer:

- clear functions
- explicit logic
- minimal abstraction
- readable code

Avoid:

- frameworks
- dependency expansion
- clever refactors
- architectural redesign

Clarity is more important than elegance.


## 9. FAILURE PROTOCOL

If any runtime failure occurs:

1. Stop execution
2. Report the exact error
3. Identify the file and line if possible
4. Do NOT apply speculative fixes
5. Await explicit user instruction


## 10. CONCEPTUAL BOUNDARY

Conceptual architecture for the project is defined in:

ARCHITECTURE.md

Cursor may reference terminology in that document, but must NOT:

- reinterpret architecture
- redesign system roles
- modify experimental design
- propose conceptual changes

Cursor's role is strictly:

coding
execution stability
schema compliance
systems engineering support


## 11. EXPERIMENTAL INTEGRITY

This project prioritizes:

- reproducibility
- disciplined iteration
- structural clarity
- minimal system drift

Cursor must avoid introducing changes that could alter experimental outcomes.


## 12. PROTECTIVE HEADER

All executable engine files should include the following header comment:

# IoS Experimental Instrument – Do Not Refactor Without Explicit Approval

This warning prevents accidental automated refactoring.


End of Cursor Operational Rules